"The sea belongs to us": a landlocked Bolivia hopes that the court will reopen the route to the Pacific.
Mariners are guarding a naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings they wave sea blue flags.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, naval bases show the motto: "The sea belongs to us by law,
It's a duty to get it back."
Throughout Bolivia, a land without sea, they still vividly remember the coast lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over the resources that took place in the 19th century, in addition to the desire to sail back through the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be the biggest in decades, as Bolivia is awaiting a resolution of the International Court of Justice by October 1 after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the impulse, a spirit of unity and serenity and of course is waiting for the result with a positive vision," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will observe the judgement of the International Court of Justice on large screens distributed throughout the country, in the hope that the Hague court will take action in favour of Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile has an obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign exit to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president, who plays a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has much to say about the resolution of Monday.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he promised in late August.
However, some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will decide in favour of Bolivia and that the situation would change little if it did.
The United Nations agency based in the Netherlands has no power to award Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the resolution of the International Court of Justice comes only six months after the final allegations indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Chilean expert Paz Zárate in international law.
Far from promoting the Bolivian cause, it may have been hampered by the past four years.
"The problem of access to the sea has been kidnapped by the current Bolivian administration," said Zárate.
In addition, he suggested that Morales' belligerent rhetoric has undermined any residual Chilean goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to speak at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to hold conversations after this.
Both countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, representative of Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that the decision-making of the court was unusually rapid.
On Monday, Bolivia will be offered an "extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile" and the possibility of " bringing an end to 139 years of mutual benefit disagreements," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents of Latin America, would use the maritime theme as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never give up her right to have access to the Pacific Ocean," he added.
"The resolution is an opportunity to see that we have to leave the past behind."
