John Edward: Language skills are fundamental to the citizens of the world
The independent educational centres in Scotland have a history of academic excellence which has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in the examinations that are reinforced by individual and collective successes collected in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (SCIS) are striving to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the centres.
As Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak a man in a language you understand, the message comes to his head.
If you speak in his tongue, he reaches his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's exams, we can observe that the languages are at the highest in the classification tables, being the highest approved rates in the independent schools.
A total of 68% of the students who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest grade.
The data collected from the 74 SCIS centres showed that 72% of the students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of the students studying German, 69% of the French students and 63% of the students in Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that the independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages for considering them a fundamental competence that both children and young people will need in the future.
At present, languages are considered to be at the same level as CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the study plans of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK Employment and Skills Commission revealed that, of the reasons given by entrepreneurs for the difficulties they faced in filling jobs, 17 % were attributed to the lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
The potential employment opportunities that require languages are increasing, so these competences are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that someone chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last all his life.
The ability to communicate directly with persons from foreign countries will enable that person to move forward automatically to competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation. It was also established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
That is why investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If children know a number of languages, especially those of developing economies, they will be equipped to have better opportunities to find a quality job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach the most important languages for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools, you can always choose between a number of languages given by teaching staff specialized in this field.
The independent educational centres in Scotland devote all their efforts to provide a learning environment that prepares children and that teams with the skills needed to succeed, whatever their future might be.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to have a vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should indeed be regarded as "competences for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it.
