On Saturday, the Minister of Foreign Affairs of North Korea informed the United Nations that the continuation of the sanctions deepened its mistrust in the United States and that there was no possibility that his country would give up nuclear weapons unilaterally under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho stated to the annual General Assembly of the international body that North Korea had taken "significant measures of goodwill" over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear testing facilities and committing itself to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we received no similar response from the United States," he said.
"If we don't have confidence in the United States, we can't have confidence in our national security, and in those circumstances, there is no possibility that we will first unilaterally disarmament."
Although Ri repeated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a formula of denuclearization "by stages" that rewards the country as it makes gradual steps, its statement is important, since it did not reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong One and Donald Trump after the first summit between an active American president and a North Korean leader on 12 June in Singapore, when Kim committed to working for the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" and Trump ensured the security of North Korea.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the war in Korea in 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted appeals to alleviate international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased pressure by means of sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner, even by objecting to a declaration of the end of the war," Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a chimera of people who don't know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our mistrust."
Ri made no mention of the plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced to the bombo and plate by the US leader to the United Nations early this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings held between Kim and Moon Jae, leader of South Korea in the last five months, adding: "If South Korea had been interested in denuclearization rather than the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be found in a similar stagnation."
