Harvard students take a course on how to rest enough
Thanks to a new course given this year at Harvard University, all university students sleep more in an attempt to fight the growing machist culture of studying all night drinking caffeine.
One professor found out that students at the number one university in the world often have no idea about the basic care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, sleep medicine professor at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, it is believed that the first of his class in the United States.
His motivation for starting the course arose after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
"At the end of the course, a girl approached and asked me why she just found out about this now, in her last year.
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," commented The Telegraph.
The course, given for the first time this year, explains to students the basic concepts of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university, said that the university decided to introduce the course after finding out that students were barely sleeping during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of sleeplessness on sports performance and the importance of establishing a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed of how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of infarction, embolism, depression and cancer.
Later, a campus icon with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know that it's not going to change the behavior of students instantly.
However, we believe that you have the right to know, just as anyone has the right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco," said Professor Czeisler.
He said that the culture of pride for "to spend the night on the sail" still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure that students are subjected to meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping enough time and a good quality dream should be the "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation makes the brain create a feeling of hunger, so they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the year before during his first year at Harvard.
He pointed out that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to extend it across the campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar curriculum before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler's recommendation is that students think of putting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that emit the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter the circadian rhythms, so they would end up having problems to stay asleep.
