Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a new company that tries to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt is the latest project of the technology legend. A company that is based on Berners-Lee's Solid Open Source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people will have access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is to "dominate the world".
"It has to be now," he said about startup.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid technology so users can create their own "online personal data storage" or a POD.
It can contain lists, pending task lists, calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in a browser at the same time.
Something that is unique in personal online data storage is that the user is the one who fully decides who can access what kind of information.
The company calls it "personal capacity through data".
Inrupt's idea, according to the company's CEO John Bruce, is to incorporate resources, processes and skills so that Solid can reach everyone.
At the moment, the company is made up of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform that bought IBM, some of the developers included in the template that were hired to work on the project and a community of volunteer programmers.
From this week on, technological developers from around the world could create their own decentralized apps with the tools available on the Inrupt website.
