The trade war between the United States and China could benefit Beijing
The first rescues of trade war between the United States and China were deafening, and although there is still much left to finish the battle, a break between countries could benefit Beijing, experts say.
Donald Trump, the President of the United States, launched the first warning early in the year by putting tariffs on the main Chinese exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminium.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new tariffs affecting $200 billion (£150,000 million) in products, which carries taxes half of the products entering the United States from China.
Beijing has, on all occasions, taken equivalent reprisals, recently applying five to ten percent tariffs to US products worth $60 billion.
China is committed to equalizing US attacks, and it is unlikely that the second most powerful economy in the world will sink soon.
Getting Washington back would mean yielding to demands, but publicly submitting to the United States would be too embarrassing for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
Even so, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, U.S. trade war pressures could positively help China in the long term by reducing interdependence between the two economies.
"The fact that a rapid political decision in Washington or Beijing can make it possible to start a crash of the economy in either of the two countries is in fact much more dangerous than the viewers have recognized so far," said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher focused on Asian issues for the strategic cabinet Center for New American Security.
Syria is ready for the return of refugees, said the Minister for Foreign Affairs
Syria claims that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help in rebuilding a country devastated by a war that has already been fought for over seven years.
In a speech earlier by the United Nations General Assembly, the Minister for Foreign Affairs, Walid al-Moualem, said that the conditions of the country were improving.
"The situation on the ground today is more stable and secure thanks to the progress achieved in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by terrorists to try to restore normality.
All the conditions for the voluntary return to the country of refugees had to be abandoned due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods had already been met.
The UN estimates that, since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people still living in the country and needing humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem recognized that the Syrian regime would appreciate the help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he also stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that promoted insurgency.
